


1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:16,560
So since the first sentence of Moby Dick is, call me Ishmael, the first thing is to talk about Ishmael, who is also, that's Melville's, so to speak, name in the book, but it's really Melville himself is Ishmael.

2
00:00:16,559 --> 00:00:19,600
And Ishmael is a wanderer.

3
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:27,200
He was Abraham's illegitimate son, cast out by Sarah when they had their own legitimate son, Isaac.

4
00:00:27,200 --> 00:00:30,239
And he then became an outcast and a wanderer.

5
00:00:30,239 --> 00:00:37,840
I take it from Melville's point of view, he's the perfect example of somebody that has no world of his own, no identity of his own.

6
00:00:38,160 --> 00:00:42,159
And notice that the writer of the book isn't even named Ishmael.

7
00:00:42,159 --> 00:00:44,000
He says, call me Ishmael.

8
00:00:44,320 --> 00:00:47,679
We don't know the name of the writer of the book.

9
00:00:47,680 --> 00:01:02,719
And also Melville, in the copy of the book that you all have, The Signet Classic, I was struck, I never saw before, a brief summary of Melville's life, which sounds pretty Ishmael-ish.

10
00:01:02,719 --> 00:01:13,199
His father's bankruptcy and death in 1832 deprived him of higher educational opportunities and put him outside the conventional view of life.

11
00:01:13,200 --> 00:01:21,519
So I didn't realize he's self-educated, knowing all the Shakespeare and Milton and Bible and Farses and so forth.

12
00:01:21,840 --> 00:01:22,799
But so what did he do?

13
00:01:22,800 --> 00:01:24,079
He taught school.

14
00:01:24,079 --> 00:01:26,239
He sailed to Liverpool and back.

15
00:01:26,240 --> 00:01:38,239
Then he shipped on another whale, on a whaling voyage, he deserted at the Marquis Islands, lived for a month among the cannibals, and came out alive.

16
00:01:38,239 --> 00:01:44,000
And then he got picked up by an Australian whale ship that took him to Tahiti, where he was jailed for mutiny.

17
00:01:44,519 --> 00:01:53,879
But he escaped and spent some months as a beach comber until a third whaling ship took him to Hawaii and then he lived there for a while.

18
00:01:53,879 --> 00:02:00,919
Talk about somebody who is rootless and has just a whole bunch of jobs, none of which define him.

19
00:02:00,920 --> 00:02:04,120
And he says that he's been teaching at the beginning of this book.

20
00:02:04,120 --> 00:02:08,519
So he obviously goes from teaching to whaling to writing.

21
00:02:08,519 --> 00:02:15,079
And through it all, and this is what begins to make it polytheistic, he's very moody.

22
00:02:15,079 --> 00:02:19,000
And his moods really tell him what to do.

23
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:40,919
So the book begins, Call Me Ishmael, and then a little further down, whenever I find myself growing grim about the mouth, whenever it's a damn drizzly November in my soul, whenever I find myself bringing up the end of every funeral procession, and so forth and so forth, then it's time for me to go to sea, he says.

24
00:02:40,920 --> 00:02:43,079
So he's dictated by his moods.

25
00:02:43,079 --> 00:02:45,560
He doesn't freely decide to go to sea.

26
00:02:45,560 --> 00:02:48,839
There's a certain time when he just has to go to sea.

27
00:02:49,079 --> 00:03:00,280
On page five, he says that there's a fate that has constant surveillance of me and dogs me and influences me in some unaccountable way.

28
00:03:00,280 --> 00:03:05,080
I take that to mean that it's always my moods that lead me and influence me.

29
00:03:05,080 --> 00:03:08,680
I don't decide what to do and when to do it.

30
00:03:08,680 --> 00:03:21,479
And that makes him all remind you of Homer and the gods who are the moods who attune people to their situations and lead them to do whatever they do.

31
00:03:21,479 --> 00:03:39,039
Now, normally I don't really pay attention to the letters and the sort of critical stuff, but there's a letter from Melville to Hawthorne, which is so illuminating and so much agrees with my interpretation that I often read it.

32
00:03:39,039 --> 00:03:46,719
So, Melville always admired Hawthorne and thought he was, Hawthorne was the great one, and Melville was sort of a failure, even as a writer.

33
00:03:46,719 --> 00:03:53,680
And that's sort of ironic, because Hawthorne is still read, but Moby Dick is more and more counted the great American novel.

34
00:03:53,680 --> 00:03:56,560
At the time, people didn't know what to make of it.

35
00:03:56,560 --> 00:04:06,960
So he says to Hawthorne, in me, divine magnanimities, magnanimities are spontaneous and instantaneous.

36
00:04:06,959 --> 00:04:08,560
Catch them while you can.

37
00:04:08,560 --> 00:04:11,839
The world goes around and another side comes up.

38
00:04:11,839 --> 00:04:17,360
I take these divine magnanimities to be the moods that catch him.

39
00:04:17,360 --> 00:04:23,759
And then he says the famous line, I've written a wicked book and feel spotless as a lamb.

40
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:43,040
Why it's a wicked book, you have to read the whole book to find out, but roughly, because it's totally anti-Christian, but it's anti-any form of supreme being, any view or culture that thinks it's got an answer to the meaning of the universe.

41
00:04:43,039 --> 00:04:52,639
It's, from Melville's point of view, everything is interpretation all the way down, which from a Christian and Hawthorne-like point of view would be a wicked book.

42
00:04:52,639 --> 00:04:54,079
But he doesn't mind.

43
00:04:54,079 --> 00:05:01,439
In fact, he's sort of the next sentence says, I don't mind having written a book that's wicked from a Christian point of view.

44
00:05:01,439 --> 00:05:03,040
I'm a polytheist.

45
00:05:03,039 --> 00:05:06,479
He says, ineffable socialities are in me.

46
00:05:06,480 --> 00:05:11,599
I would sit down and dine with you and all the gods in old Rome's pantheon.

47
00:05:11,600 --> 00:05:14,680
That he should have said Greeks, but he doesn't seem to know much about Greek.

48
00:05:14,680 --> 00:05:18,840
He knows all the antiquity stuff from the Roman.

49
00:05:18,839 --> 00:05:19,800
But there it is.

50
00:05:13,759 --> 00:05:21,080
He feels fine.

51
00:05:21,240 --> 00:05:22,759
He's written his book.

52
00:05:22,759 --> 00:05:39,639
His book is utterly anti-anything which later in the course or already in the course, starting with Dante, we've called onto theology, the idea that there is some supreme being in which everything is grounded and which you can make sense of it.

53
00:05:39,639 --> 00:05:50,040
And one more moody remark, which is, if anybody knows Foucault, you'll recognize Foucault said the same thing 150 years later.

54
00:05:50,040 --> 00:05:51,000
Or is it 200?

55
00:05:51,480 --> 00:05:52,120
200?

56
00:05:52,439 --> 00:05:55,800
1850, this is, well, 170 or something.

57
00:05:55,800 --> 00:05:57,000
I'm bad at arithmetic.

58
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:00,520
So here's what he ends up saying to Hawthorne in this letter.

59
00:06:00,519 --> 00:06:03,560
This is a long letter, but you're not bound to answer it.

60
00:06:03,560 --> 00:06:08,840
Possibly, if you do answer it and direct it to Herman Melville, you will missend it.

61
00:06:08,840 --> 00:06:15,399
For the very fingers that now guide this pen are not precisely the same that just took it up and put it on this paper.

62
00:06:15,399 --> 00:06:17,960
Lord, when shall we be done changing?

63
00:06:18,279 --> 00:06:25,240
And that's just so perfect for the way the book works that I couldn't resist reading it.

64
00:06:25,240 --> 00:06:26,839
So here we are.

65
00:06:26,840 --> 00:06:40,599
Ishmael is like Odysseus, only even more of a wanderer, because Odysseus has a home to go to, finally, where his wife and Penelope and Telemachus are waiting for him.

66
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:42,520
Ishmael is a total wanderer.

67
00:06:42,519 --> 00:06:47,800
He has no home and no family, the way it's uh set up here.

68
00:06:47,800 --> 00:06:55,080
No job, no olive tree bed that's anchored in the earth because as uh Odysseus has.

69
00:06:55,399 --> 00:06:58,040
And in fact, he has no roots at all.

70
00:06:58,039 --> 00:07:03,120
And he lives in a whole range of possible worlds.

71
00:06:58,840 --> 00:07:05,680
Now I wonder why I said possible worlds.

72
00:07:05,920 --> 00:07:10,800
I think a whole range of worlds is all it is that I want to say.

73
00:07:10,800 --> 00:07:15,680
And he wants to be at home in all of them.

74
00:07:15,680 --> 00:07:22,079
And he says this on, I'll keep reading little things because I want to keep you in touch with the text.

75
00:07:22,079 --> 00:07:30,719
So he says, I love to sail, listen to Ishmael now, I love to sail forbidden seas and land on barbarous coasts, not ignoring what is good.

76
00:07:30,720 --> 00:07:35,439
I'm quick to perceive a horror and could still be social with it, would they let me?

77
00:07:35,439 --> 00:07:41,120
Since it is well to be on friendly terms with all the inmates of the place one lodges in.

78
00:07:41,439 --> 00:07:49,040
And that is, in other words, be at home in all the worlds that you can travel to.

79
00:07:49,680 --> 00:07:57,599
And he gets pulled into lots of different worlds, as Ads did Melville, as you could see from what I read.

80
00:07:57,600 --> 00:08:03,120
And in each, he respects the gods of that world.

81
00:08:03,439 --> 00:08:19,120
And when Kleequeg, the black savage, shows up and is worshiping his god, Yo-Yo, then Melville, or Ishmael, worships Yo-Yo.

82
00:08:19,120 --> 00:08:27,440
And he's the total enemy of what I sometimes call monolithic monotheism.

83
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:30,159
What I once said Nietzsche calls monotonot in a theism.

84
00:08:30,159 --> 00:08:31,600
I think he would agree.

85
00:08:31,600 --> 00:08:42,879
And he's against it because it excludes being open to all those gods and all those worlds, all those understandings of the sacred that you can be, let yourself be pulled into.

86
00:08:42,879 --> 00:08:43,719
No willpower.

87
00:08:43,519 --> 00:08:51,400
Just get in, if you get attuned, if your mood attunes you to them, then you take up their sense of the sacred.

88
00:08:51,720 --> 00:08:54,440
And that doesn't mean that any of them are true.

89
00:08:54,440 --> 00:08:58,120
Being true or not true just isn't the point.

90
00:08:58,120 --> 00:09:11,960
Being sacred, being something that is important to people in a way that I'll explain in a minute, is what makes them valuable, not that they get it right about the universe.

91
00:09:11,960 --> 00:09:14,840
There is no way to get it right about the universe.

92
00:09:14,840 --> 00:09:19,080
Later he'll say that Moby Dick has no face.

93
00:09:19,080 --> 00:09:25,960
That is, there's no right way to draw the way Moby Dick looks, because there's no way Moby Dick looks.

94
00:09:26,600 --> 00:09:43,480
But anybody who thinks there's one right answer to the world and our place in it is humorless, fanatical, dangerous, a philosopher, which he thinks is somebody who tries to think they've got the one right answer.

95
00:09:43,480 --> 00:09:48,520
So he says that he wants to be at home with every religion.

96
00:09:48,519 --> 00:09:51,879
See, this is a kind of higher polytheism, as you can see.

97
00:09:51,879 --> 00:09:58,040
I mean, in the polytheism, there was one religion, and something like ten gods and goddesses.

98
00:09:58,039 --> 00:10:01,320
Now it's polyreligionism or something.

99
00:10:01,319 --> 00:10:04,120
There's a whole bunch of religions out there.

100
00:10:04,120 --> 00:10:18,120
And not only do you get in tune with the various, say, ten gods of, you know, Aries, the aggressive god and Aphrodite, the erotic goddess, and so forth, and you can get in tune with those we talked about in the Odyssey.

101
00:10:18,120 --> 00:10:21,160
You can get in tune with all sorts of religions.

102
00:10:21,159 --> 00:10:25,320
And the place where he explains that most is on page 79.

103
00:10:25,319 --> 00:10:32,480
He says in the third sentence, I cherish the greatest respect toward everybody's religious obligations, never mind how comical.

104
00:10:32,799 --> 00:10:51,519
See, he thinks that it's comical that Kuikleg worships this little wooden statue, Yo-Yo, and kisses Yo-Yo on the nose before going to bed, but he does it too, and not ironically, and not laughing, laughing at it or with it or something, but in no way putting it down.

105
00:10:51,519 --> 00:10:57,920
He thinks that Kuikweg is a sort of saint and that his religion is a very good religion.

106
00:10:58,240 --> 00:11:12,960
But he says in the next paragraph, I say we good Presbyterian Christians should be charitable in these things and not fancy ourselves so vastly superior to other mortals, pagans and whatnot, because of their half-crazy conceits on this subject.

107
00:11:12,960 --> 00:11:28,800
And then comes a very important sentence that he never explains at the end of that paragraph: Heaven have mercy on all of us, Presbyterians and pagans alike, for we are all somehow dreadfully cracked about the head and sadly need mending.

108
00:11:28,799 --> 00:11:34,319
There's something fundamentally incomplete or wrong about human beings.

109
00:11:34,319 --> 00:11:39,120
I mean, from a Christian point of view, it would be sin, but in some pagan culture, it would be something else.

110
00:11:39,120 --> 00:11:45,759
But there's something that people need that religion can satisfy, that the sacred can satisfy.

111
00:11:45,759 --> 00:11:55,280
And it doesn't have to be the supreme being, as in Dante, that gives you the total satisfaction when you stare into God's depths.

112
00:11:55,279 --> 00:11:57,760
But something has to heal you.

113
00:11:57,759 --> 00:12:07,120
And since I was just reading near the end of the book today, when Quique gets very sick and almost dies, he doesn't die.

114
00:12:07,120 --> 00:12:12,240
And he looks completely serene and happy in his illness.

115
00:12:13,879 --> 00:12:23,720
And it's clear that he's been, though he's fit physically, he's been healed spiritually.

116
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:25,720
And those words are connected.

117
00:12:25,720 --> 00:12:36,440
Being healed, being healthy, being holy, in German, Heil, which does all this job in one word, is what he's talking about here.

118
00:12:36,440 --> 00:12:38,600
Human beings need that.

119
00:12:39,080 --> 00:12:40,360
He needs that.

120
00:12:40,360 --> 00:12:46,920
In his view, the more versions of the healing that you can get attuned to, the better.

121
00:12:47,559 --> 00:12:50,920
If anybody wants to say anything, by the way, feel free to interrupt.

122
00:12:50,919 --> 00:12:54,759
This vast number of people out there must have many questions on that.

123
00:12:56,840 --> 00:13:00,199
So now we're on the next issue.

124
00:13:00,200 --> 00:13:04,680
That was the sort of background polytheism, which will become clearer as we go on.

125
00:13:04,679 --> 00:13:13,160
Now comes Ishmael on the mysterious, the fundamentally mysterious and indefinite nature of reality.

126
00:13:13,159 --> 00:13:21,000
It's the experience of this kind of indefinite mysteriousness that keeps you open to all the worlds.

127
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:25,240
Once you think you've got an answer, then you just have the answer.

128
00:13:25,240 --> 00:13:34,279
But if you understand that not only you don't have the answer, but the very idea that there is an answer is wrong, then you're open to everything.

129
00:13:34,279 --> 00:13:35,480
Aha, I knew you'd have to.

130
00:13:39,399 --> 00:13:48,600
No, no, you don't need the variety, but you're onto something puzzling about this whole book because it, let's try to think about it.

131
00:13:48,600 --> 00:13:52,120
Certainly, he thinks that any one of the particular ones will do.

132
00:13:52,120 --> 00:14:02,480
There's only one kind of religion that doesn't heal you, and that's Christianity and all the onto-theological religions who think they have one, the one truth.

133
00:14:02,799 --> 00:14:14,560
But otherwise, he talks about visiting various places in the course of the book where he sits down and goes to their temples or drinks their drugs or whatever it is that their religion has.

134
00:14:14,559 --> 00:14:24,000
Now, why does he think, or does he, that it's better to be open to many of them than to just be living in one of them?

135
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:26,320
That's a very, very, very good question.

136
00:14:26,320 --> 00:14:28,080
It should have been a paper talk.

137
00:14:29,679 --> 00:14:35,760
And the first thing to say is, generally, he doesn't think that many is a good thing.

138
00:14:35,759 --> 00:14:42,000
He's perfectly happy with Quequeg's pagan religion healing him.

139
00:14:42,320 --> 00:14:51,439
But there's something about the situation of Western 19th-century human beings that makes it necessary.

140
00:14:51,440 --> 00:15:01,840
I'm thinking out loud, I don't know the answer yet, makes it necessary for them to collect the sacred here and there wherever it locally manifests itself.

141
00:15:01,840 --> 00:15:04,720
At least it's necessary for Ishmael for some reason.

142
00:15:04,720 --> 00:15:12,320
Now, and I take it it's for Ishmael qua modern, uprooted, post-Christian person.

143
00:15:12,320 --> 00:15:16,720
Now, why can't he just settle down with one of these religions?

144
00:15:16,720 --> 00:15:20,879
Why is he collecting openness to the sacred?

145
00:15:21,519 --> 00:15:24,319
Yes, but that's just the name of the question in a way.

146
00:15:24,639 --> 00:15:38,720
Why does he think being open to cross-cultural sacredness is a good religion for him instead of settling down with Quiqueg, for instance, and taking up his religion?

147
00:15:38,720 --> 00:15:45,320
It seems somehow this is not very satisfactory, what I'm saying, but that there's just a feeling of the more sacred, the better.

148
00:15:45,639 --> 00:15:53,160
And that once you've gotten loose from any particular culture, you go and experience them all.

149
00:15:53,480 --> 00:15:59,879
And that's somehow, I haven't really answered you, an advantage over the ones that are in each particular one.

150
00:15:59,879 --> 00:16:06,120
Somehow you get more of you healed, or different ways you're cracked about the head get healed, or something.

151
00:16:06,120 --> 00:16:07,080
Ah, good.

152
00:16:07,399 --> 00:16:08,759
Yes, you're right.

153
00:16:08,759 --> 00:16:09,799
Let's put that in.

154
00:16:09,799 --> 00:16:10,920
We're coming to that.

155
00:16:11,159 --> 00:16:20,040
But yes, there's something about the indefiniteness which is important.

156
00:16:20,039 --> 00:16:22,519
But you see, you turned it the other way than I turn it.

157
00:16:22,519 --> 00:16:29,720
I think it's because there is this basic indefiniteness in the universe that he's open to all these sacreds.

158
00:16:29,720 --> 00:16:33,719
And you think that what?

159
00:16:34,759 --> 00:16:35,959
I will say what you said again.

160
00:16:35,960 --> 00:16:37,720
It seemed to me not what I said just.

161
00:16:45,399 --> 00:16:47,639
The mood is important part of it.

162
00:16:47,879 --> 00:16:50,279
That's the sort of super polytheism.

163
00:16:50,279 --> 00:17:01,799
Just as there's not just one goddess, a god or goddess in the pantheon, how you have to be sensitive to being aggressive, to being domestic, to being erotic, to being a sort of nerd like Festus.

164
00:17:02,119 --> 00:17:02,839
Why?

165
00:17:04,680 --> 00:17:13,000
And it seems that it just takes all of these because you have all these various capacities to exercise.

166
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:25,640
So since there are all these moods, and since different religions you get attuned to through different moods, somehow, of course, we're getting to the same non-question.

167
00:17:25,640 --> 00:17:42,400
Somehow, the more moods you can use and the more things you can get attuned to, there's a place where he talks about why he doesn't want to be just looking at the sun.

168
00:17:42,400 --> 00:17:43,599
Well, no, this is the same thing.

169
00:17:43,599 --> 00:17:46,319
He certainly doesn't want to be just looking at God.

170
00:17:46,319 --> 00:17:48,480
And he certainly doesn't want to be in despair.

171
00:17:48,480 --> 00:17:50,319
We'll talk about that later.

172
00:17:50,319 --> 00:17:57,599
But we're still back to the question, what's the advantage of experiencing all these different moods?

173
00:17:57,599 --> 00:18:11,359
I think all I can say is they're there, if you're capable of them, and each one of them gives you some insight into what you are and some kind of satisfaction or meaning, then the more the better.

174
00:18:11,359 --> 00:18:12,880
That's the best I can do.

175
00:18:12,880 --> 00:18:13,200
Yeah.

176
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:20,639
I wish that every school plays this level of connection to one world to another.

177
00:18:20,640 --> 00:18:23,599
Then you can find all these different.

178
00:18:24,160 --> 00:18:29,759
And he that's nice, but why not embody just one sacred?

179
00:18:29,759 --> 00:18:39,039
You don't know this yet, really, unless you've, I don't know how far you've gotten in the reading, but Quiqueg, I talked about it in the last lecture, embodies one sacred.

180
00:18:39,039 --> 00:18:44,720
It's carved on his body by the prophet of his tribe, and he's saved.

181
00:18:44,720 --> 00:18:47,839
So what's the advantage?

182
00:18:47,839 --> 00:18:49,599
I think, again, I get this feeling.

183
00:18:49,599 --> 00:19:02,639
Well, that would be fine if Melville had a tradition that had in it the sacred and the divine anymore, if it hadn't lost it, and if he had been brought up in those practices and they were carved into his body, he would be saved.

184
00:19:02,640 --> 00:19:05,279
But he can't, he's this postmodern person.

185
00:19:05,279 --> 00:19:10,799
He can't just take over his tradition the way Quiqueg can as a saving theme.

186
00:19:10,799 --> 00:19:11,039
Yeah.

187
00:19:11,360 --> 00:19:14,199
Well, education is kind of trying to learn a little bit about it.

188
00:19:14,599 --> 00:19:26,759
I think that may be a sort of psychological explanation about Ishmael, but the fact that he didn't go to Oxford or Berkeley makes him open maybe in some special way.

189
00:19:26,759 --> 00:19:45,319
But he's certainly trying to say that given the way things are, openness to moods and worlds is, of course, he says it's how he is, but I think he means is that's how anybody is who's sensitive to the way things are and knows how to get healed.

190
00:19:45,319 --> 00:19:49,079
Okay, now that'll give me plenty to think about.

191
00:19:49,079 --> 00:19:50,439
Now let me see.

192
